Yes, both are known MSTest v4 behavioral changes:

**1. Tests appear as new in Azure DevOps** — The `TestCase.Id` generation algorithm changed in v4 to fix bugs. There's no code fix; your test history will re-baseline from this point forward.

**2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`** — v4 now enforces lifecycle scope. `TestName` is per-test, so it's not available in class-level init. Move that access to `[TestInitialize]` or individual test methods.

**Other behavioral changes to watch for:**

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Tests not discovered | `TreatDiscoveryWarningsAsErrors` now defaults to `true` | Fix discovery warnings or set to `false` in `.runsettings` |
| Tests hang on .NET Framework | AppDomain disabled by default | Set `DisableAppDomain` to `false` in `.runsettings` |
| `vstest.console` finds 0 tests (MSTest.Sdk) | Sdk defaults to MTP mode, no `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` | Add the package or use `dotnet test` |
| New warnings from analyzers | Several analyzers upgraded from Info→Warning | Fix or suppress in `.editorconfig` |

For the `TestContext.TestName` fix specifically:

```csharp
// Before — throws in v4
[ClassInitialize]
public static void Init(TestContext ctx)
{
    var name = ctx.TestName; // ❌ throws
}

// After — move to TestInitialize
[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    var name = TestContext.TestName; // ✅ works here
}
```

Would you like me to inspect your project files for any other v4 issues?
